{('Coder Initials', 'Unnamed: 0_level_1', 'Unnamed: 0_level_2'): {2: 'ALL', 3: nan}, ('Article ID', 'Unnamed: 1_level_1', 'Unnamed: 1_level_2'): {2: 'BSMA0001', 3: 'BSMA0002'}, ('Sample ID', 'Unnamed: 2_level_1', 'Unnamed: 2_level_2'): {2: 'BSMA0001.1', 3: nan}, ('Effect size ID', 'Unnamed: 3_level_1', 'Unnamed: 3_level_2'): {2: 'BSMA0001.1.3', 3: nan}, ('Inclusion-\nExclusion Judgment', 'Unnamed: 4_level_1', 'Unnamed: 4_level_2'): {2: '1 = Include', 3: nan}, ('Reason for Exclusion', 'Unnamed: 5_level_1', 'Unnamed: 5_level_2'): {2: nan, 3: nan}, ('Article Descriptors', 'Unnamed: 6_level_1', 'Abstract'): {2: 'Drawing on the job demands�resources model, we suggest and test a motivational mechanism that underlies the relationship between leader boundary-spanning behavior and employee voice behavior. Based on the field survey data of 383 leader-employee pairs collected from various organizations in South Korea, the results of our mediation model showed that leader boundary-spanning behavior, as a potential job resource, enhances employee voice behavior by increasing employee self-efficacy. The results of our moderated mediation model also showed that the focal leader�s abusive supervision, as a potential job demand, could attenuate the beneficial effect of leader boundary-spanning behavior on employee voice behavior by diminishing employee self-efficacy. These findings highlight the importance of leader boundary-spanning behavior in enhancing employee voice behavior, the roles of employee self-efficacy as a key mediating mechanism, and the focal leader�s abusive supervision as a preventable boundary condition within these relationships. Theoretical and practical implications are discussed.', 3: 'The public sector is increasingly collaborating with the private sector in the development of large-scale public infrastructure projects. However, the difficulties arising due to working across organizational boundaries are often detrimental to project performance. This article argues that boundary-spanning activities can enhance the quality of collaboration and subsequently the performance of projects. Boundary spanners utilize relational governance mechanisms and undertake conscious endeavors for building interorganizational relationships by engaging in activities, such as coordination and communication with the stakeholders. The data for this study are composed of 158 survey responses from lead public managers involved in Dutch national public infrastructure projects. The data are analyzed using structural equation modeling. The study demonstrates that the quality of collaboration has a significant impact on the performance of the project during the implementation phase. Further, we find that the different boundary-spanning activities are interconnected and that they have a significant positive relationship on project performance, with a mediating effect of collaboration. The study concludes that, and shows how boundary spanners are vital to the collaborative processes through which public infrastructure projects are implemented.'}, ('Article Descriptors', 'Unnamed: 7_level_1', 'Title'): {2: 'Leader Boundary-Spanning Behavior and Employee Voice Behavior: The Job Demands�Resources Perspective', 3: 'The Impact of Boundary Spanning by Public Managers on Collaboration and Infrastructure Project Performance'}, ('Article Descriptors', 'Unnamed: 8_level_1', 'Publication Name'): {2: 'Behavioral Sciences', 3: 'Public Performance & Management Review\xa0'}, ('Article Descriptors', 'Unnamed: 9_level_1', 'Authors'): {2: 'Lee, J., Choi, D., & Cheong, M.', 3: 'Satheesh, S. A., Verweij, S., van Meerkerk, I., Busscher, T., & Arts, J.'}, ('Article Descriptors', 'Unnamed: 10_level_1', 'Year'): {2: 2023, 3: 2023}, ('Article Descriptors', 'Unnamed: 11_level_1', 'Publication Type'): {2: '1 = Journal article', 3: nan}, ('Article Descriptors', 'Unnamed: 12_level_1', 'Other (specify)'): {2: nan, 3: nan}, ('Article Descriptors', 'Unnamed: 13_level_1', 'Full Citation (APA Style)'): {2: nan, 3: nan}, ('Article Descriptors', 'Unnamed: 14_level_1', 'Secondary Data? (If yes, provide reference to the original paper)'): {2: nan, 3: nan}, ('Article Descriptors', 'Unnamed: 15_level_1', 'Notes'): {2: nan, 3: nan}, ('Study/Sample Descriptors', 'Unnamed: 16_level_1', 'Study Design'): {2: '1 = Cross-sectional', 3: nan}, ('Study/Sample Descriptors', 'Unnamed: 17_level_1', 'Other (specify)'): {2: nan, 3: nan}, ('Study/Sample Descriptors', 'Unnamed: 18_level_1', 'Country'): {2: 'South Korea', 3: nan}, ('Study/Sample Descriptors', 'Unnamed: 19_level_1', 'Country (specify)'): {2: nan, 3: nan}, ('Study/Sample Descriptors', 'Unnamed: 20_level_1', 'International Context'): {2: '1 = No (domestic only)', 3: nan}, ('Study/Sample Descriptors', 'Unnamed: 21_level_1', 'Sample size (N)'): {2: 383.0, 3: nan}, ('Study/Sample Descriptors', 'Unnamed: 22_level_1', 'Mean Age'): {2: 43.4, 3: nan}, ('Study/Sample Descriptors', 'Unnamed: 23_level_1', '% Female'): {2: 19.0, 3: nan}, ('Study/Sample Descriptors', 'Unnamed: 24_level_1', 'Org Tenure'): {2: 999.0, 3: nan}, ('Study/Sample Descriptors', 'Unnamed: 25_level_1', 'Occupation Type'): {2: ' employees of business\norganizations in various industries, including manufacturing, telecommunication, and\nservice sectors', 3: nan}, ('Measure Descriptors', 'Boundary spanning', 'Number of Items'): {2: 6.0, 3: nan}, ('Measure Descriptors', 'Boundary spanning', 'Min Score'): {2: 1.0, 3: nan}, ('Measure Descriptors', 'Boundary spanning', 'Max Score'): {2: 7.0, 3: nan}, ('Measure Descriptors', 'Boundary spanning', 'Report Type'): {2: '3 = Others (e.g. coworker/peer subordinate customer/client)', 3: nan}, ('Measure Descriptors', 'Boundary spanning', 'Report Type Note (if necessary)'): {2: 'employees (subordinate)', 3: nan}, ('Measure Descriptors', 'Boundary spanning', 'Specific Measure Used'): {2: 'Marrone et al. (2007)', 3: nan}, ('Measure Descriptors', 'Boundary spanning', 'Notes'): {2: nan, 3: nan}, ('Measure Descript